To find (A × B) ∪ (A × C), we first need to find the Cartesian products A × B and A × C, and then find their union.

A × B = {(a, b) | a ∈ A, b ∈ B} = {(1, x), (1, y), (2, x), (2, y), (3, x), (3, y)}

A × C = {(a, c) | a ∈ A, c ∈ C} = {(1, z), (2, z), (3, z)}

Now, we find the union of these two sets:

(A × B) ∪ (A × C) = {(1, x), (1, y), (2, x), (2, y), (3, x), (3, y)} ∪ {(1, z), (2, z), (3, z)}

(A × B) ∪ (A × C) = {(1, x), (1, y), (2, x), (2, y), (3, x), (3, y), (1, z), (2, z), (3, z)}

So, (A × B) ∪ (A × C) is the set {(1, x), (1, y), (2, x), (2, y), (3, x), (3, y), (1, z), (2, z), (3, z)}.
